  June 13,  2014</strong>  Christian Science Monitor    Digital addictions mean we can't read books anymore. And that's a problem.</strong>      
Chances are that in the next few seconds, something will lure you away from this essay: An incoming text, an email, a sexier headline on this page, even a link within this piece... Office workers are interrupted – or they self-interrupt – roughly every three minutes, according to recent studies. And it can take some 23 minutes for a worker to return to the original task. That is according to an article in the Wall Street Journal that refers to the work of  Gloria Mark</strong>, a professor of informatics at the University of California, Irvine, who studies digital distraction.






  
 Read the full story on the
 Christian Science Monitor  
website. 


   
   
   
  Digital addictions mean we can't read books anymore. And that's a problem. 
 
 
  
